Let us illustrate the problem with an example. Suppose a table T𝑇T
is to be anonymized for publication. Table T𝑇T has two kinds of
attributes, the quasi-identifier (QI) attributes and the sensitive
attribute. The QI attributes
can be used as an identifier
in the table.
[24] points out that in a real dataset, most individuals can be uniquely identified by three QI attributes,
namely sex, date of birth and 5-digit zip code. The sensitive
attribute contains some sensitive values. In our example,
Table 1 is the given table T𝑇T where one of the QI
attributes is “Nationality" and the sensitive attribute is
“Disease" containing sensitive values such as Heart Disease and
HIV. Note that there can be other QI attributes in this table such
as sex and zip code. For the sake of illustration, we list
attribute “Nationality" only.
Assume that each tuple in the table is owned by an
individual and each individual owns at most one tuple.

Let P𝑃P be a partition of table T𝑇T.
We give a unique ID called GID to this partition P𝑃P
and append an additional attribute called GID to this partition where
each tuple in P𝑃P has the same GID value.
Existing group-based anonymization defines a function β𝛽\beta on P𝑃P to
form an A-group such that
the linkage between the QI attributes
and the sensitive attribute in the A-group is lost.
There are two ways in the literature for this task.
One is generalization by generalizing
all QI values to the same value. The other is
bucketization by
forming two tables, called the QI
table and the sensitive table, where
P𝑃P is projected on all QI attributes and attribute GID
to form the QI table, and on
the sensitive attribute and attribute GID to form the
sensitive table.
A table T𝑇T is anonymized to a dataset T∗superscript𝑇T^{*} if
T∗superscript𝑇T^{*} is formed by first partitioning T𝑇T into a number
of partitions, then forming an A-group from
each partition by β𝛽\beta and finally inserting each A-group into T∗superscript𝑇T^{*}.
For example, Table 1 is anonymized to
Table 2 by bucketization.

In known voter registration lists,
the QI values can often be used to identify a unique individual
[24, 16]. We assume that there is a
mapping which maps each tuple in T𝑇T to an A-group in T∗superscript𝑇T^{*}.
For example, the first tuple t1subscript𝑡1t_{1} in
Table 1 is mapped to A-group L1subscript𝐿1L_{1}.

For illustration, a simplified setting of the l𝑙l-diversity model
[21] is used as a privacy requirement for published
data T∗superscript𝑇T^{*}. An A-group is said to be l𝑙l-diverse or satisfy
l𝑙l-diversity if in the A-group the number of occurrences
of any sensitive value is at most 1/l1𝑙1/l of the group size. A table
satisfies l𝑙l-diversity (or it is
l𝑙l-diverse) if all A-groups in it are l𝑙l-diverse. Table 2 satisfies 2-diversity. The intention is
that each individual cannot be linked to a disease with a
probability of more than 0.5. However, does this table protect
individual privacy sufficiently?

Let us examine the A-group with GID equal to L1subscript𝐿1L_{1}
as shown in Table 2. We also refer to the A-group by Lisubscript𝐿𝑖L_{i}. In L1subscript𝐿1L_{1}, Heart Disease and
Flu are values of the sensitive attribute Disease. It seems
that each of the two individuals, Alex and Bob, in this group has a
50% chance of linking to Heart Disease (Flu). The reason why the
chance is interpreted as 50% is that the analysis is based on this
group locally without any additional information.

In Table 2, there are only two local possible worlds for assigning the
disease values to the two individuals in L1subscript𝐿1L_{1}: (1) w1::subscript𝑤1absentw_{1}: Alex is
linked to Heart Disease and Bob is linked to Flu and (2) w2::subscript𝑤2absentw_{2}: Alex
is linked to Flu and Bob is linked to Heart Disease. To construct a
probability distribution over the domain of the real world, a
simplest definition is based on the assumption that all the
possible worlds are equally likely, or each world has the
same probability.
